The volume of electronic transactions done via the NIBSS Instant Payment (NIP) rose from 109.55 million to 126.56 million as the value rose to N10.73 trillion from N9.62 trillion as a total of 4.19 million customers were issued Bank Verification Numbers (BVN) by financial institutions in the country last year. Data released by the NIBSS, total BVN enrolment stood at 40.59 million as at January 12, 2020. With NIBSS’ Electronic Payments Fact sheet for January to December 2018 showing  that total BVN enrolments stood at 36.4 million at the end of December 2018, it means that a total of 4.07 million new BVNs were  issued in 2019. In 2018, total new BVN enrolment stood at about 5.7 million Volume of transactions done via the channel had grown from 101.03 million in September to 106.51 million in October while value of transactions rose from N8.48 trillion in September to N9.33 trillion. Meanwhile,  the financial inclusion drive of the Central Bank of Nigeria seems to be taking its toll as the number of active savings account soared between November and December last year, despite a significant drop in corporate accounts. Data provided by the Nigeria Inter Bank Settlement System (NIBSS) showed that active savings account rose by 4.62 million or 5.06 per cent within one month from 91.29 million as at the end of November last year to 95.91 million as at the end of December 2019. The rise recorded in the last month of the year is faster compared to 1.625 million or 1.8 per cent addition to the number of active savings account within 11 months. By the end of January last year, total number of savings was 89.66 million. However, the number of active corporate accounts have been on the decline as it dropped to 25.28 million by the end of the year compared to 25.96 million which it was in January last year. The number of active corporate accounts had risen in the course of the year to 29.8 million by the end of November before the dropped sharply by 15 per cent. Sources in the banking industry told Leadership that the rise in the number of saving account could be traced to the financial inclusion drive of the CBN. A source in the one of the tier one banks, noted that the bank had seen increase in both corporate and savings account openings, although he could note speak for an industry wide data. The source noted that the drive to increase lending to small businesses had led to increased corporate account openings by small businesses while savings account opening had increased with the financial inclusion drive of the CBN. Head of savings at Fidelity Bank, Janet Nnabuko, while speaking on a promo by the bank to encourage a savings culture noted that the bank had seen a surge in account openings as sell as savings since it commenced the Get Alert in Millions Season 4 which kicked off in October last year. According to her, the promo had been driven by the bank’s commitment to increasing financial inclusion in the country and help its customers imbibe a savings culture. The promo which is the Industry watchers note that the NIBSS told Leadership that the spike in savings account could be as a result of reactivation of old accounts and opening of new accounts as financial inclusion figures improve, while the drop in corporate accounts could be a result of accounts going dormant. Total active accounts in the industry had grown from 71.79 million in January 2019 to 79.21 million in November and 79.28 million in December. Likewise the total number of bank accounts in the country had grown from 118.97 million in January to 124.65 million in November and 124.84 million in December last year.